{{Politics of Uruguay}}
A '''referendum on partially repealing the law on public enterprises''' was held in [[Uruguay]] on 13 December 1992.<ref name=DD>[http://www.sudd.ch/event.php?lang=en&id=uy011992 Uruguay, 13 December 1992: Partial repeal of the law on public enterprises] Direct Democracy {{de icon}}</ref> The proposed repeal was approved by 73% of voters.
==Background== On 10 January 1991 the [[General Assembly of Uruguay|General Assembly]] passed law 16,211 (Law on Public Enterprises), which allowed for the [[privatisation]] of some state enterprises.<ref name=DD/>
Two attempts were made to gain enough support to force a referendum, with a quorum of 25% of registered voters required - equivalent to 589,823 voters. The first attempt gained 448,265 in favour for a partial repeal and 21,473 for a full repeal. The second effort obtained 693,668 for a partial repeal and 14,960 for a full repeal. On 15 October 1992 the [[Electoral Court of Uruguay|Electoral Court]] decided on a referendum on a partial repeal.<ref name=DD/>
==Results== {| class=wikitable style=text-align:right !Choice !Votes !% |- |align=left|For||1,293,016||72.55 |- |align=left|Against||489,302||27.45 |- |align=left|Unevaluated votes||100,191||– |- |align=left|Invalid/blank votes||59,309||– |- |align=left|'''Total'''||'''1,941,829'''||'''100''' |- |align=left|Registered voters/turnout||2,345,077||82.80 |- |align=left colspan=3|Source: [http://www.sudd.ch/event.php?lang=en&id=uy011992 Direct Democracy] |}
Unevaluated votes were those cast by voters outside of their local polling station. They would have been examined after a court had decided on their validity, but as the result was already clear, they were not counted.<ref name=DD/>
